{{Infobox football biography | name= Jenő Ábrahám | image= | fullname = Jenő Ábrahám | birth_date = | birth_place = [[Szeged]], [[Austria-Hungary]] | death_date = | death_place = | height = | currentclub = | position = [[Midfielder]] | youthyears1 = | youthyears2 = | youthclubs1 = | youthclubs2 = | years1 = {{0|0000}}–1922 | years2 = 1922–1924 | years3 = 1924–1925 | years4 = 1925–1926 | years5 = 1926–1930 | clubs1 = [[Szegedi AK]] | clubs2 = [[FK Vojvodina|Vojvodina]] | clubs3 = [[Szegedi AK]] | clubs4 = [[HŠK Građanski Zagreb|Građanski Zagreb]] | clubs5 = [[Szegedi AK|Bástya Szeged]] | caps1 = ? | caps2 = ? | caps3 = 3 | caps4 = 3 | caps5 = 41 | goals1 = ? | goals2 = ? | goals3 = 1 | goals4 = 1 | goals5 = 5 | nationalyears1 = 1922–1923 | nationalteam1 = [[Yugoslavia national football team|Kingdom of SCS]] | nationalcaps1 = 2 | nationalgoals1 = 2 | pcupdate = | ntupdate = }}
{{Eastern name order|Ábrahám Jenő}} '''Jenő Ábrahám''' ({{lang-sh-Latn|Jeno Abraham}}, {{lang-sr-Cyrl|Јено Абрахам}}) was a [[Hungary|Hungarian]] and [[Kingdom of Yugoslavia|Yugoslav]] international [[Association football|football]] player.
Born in [[Szeged]], Hungary, he started playing in his hometown club [[Szegedi AK]] (SZAK). In 1922 he came to Yugoslavia to play in [[FK Vojvodina]]. In September 1924 he was back in Hungary playing with SZAK.<ref>Sportista, n 32, Belgrade September 22, 1924, page 1</ref> In summer 1925 he moved to another Yugoslav club, the [[Zagreb]] giants [[Građanski Zagreb|1. HŠK Građanski]] where he would play one season and win the [[1926 Yugoslav First League]].<ref>[http://www.exyufudbal.in.rs/igraci/article/136 Jenő Ábrahám Yugoslav First League stats] at exyufudbal.in.rs</ref> He usually played as left-winger.<ref>[http://www.fkvojvodina.com/forum/viewtopic.php?p=54552&sid=46389dd23bd1f720964b296dc0ca043a Abraham Geza Saraz] at vojvodina.com</ref> In 1926 he left Yugoslavia and joined [[Szegedi AK|Bástya]] playing with them in the [[Nemzeti Bajnokság I|Hungarian Championship]] between 1926 and 1930.<ref>[http://www.nela.hu/nb_jatekos.php?id=7951 Jenő Ábrahám NBI stats] at nela.hu</ref>
Between 1922 and 1923, he played two matches for the [[Yugoslavia national football team]] while playing with Vojvodina<ref>[http://www.eu-football.info/_player.php?id=18482 Géza Ábrahám "Sarasz"] at EU_Football.info</ref> having scored two goals. He participated, and scored twice, in the friendly match played on 28 July 1922 in Zagreb against [[Czechoslovakia national football team|Czechoslovakia]], which was a first ever win of the Yugoslav national team, with a final result of 4-3. His other, and last, match was a year later, on 3 July 1923, in a friendly match in [[Kraków]], against [[Poland national football team|Poland]], a 2-1 win.
Born as ''Jenő Ábrahám'' ({{lang-hu|Ábrahám Jenő}}), while playing in Yugoslavia, and in the national team, he was recorded in the chronicles as "Saraz", a Serbo-Croatian transliteration of the Hungarian word "Száraz", which means "Dry" in Hungarian, a name he received probably because of his looks. Many websites confuse Jenő Ábrahám with Eugen "Geza" Ábrahám. The two played in FK Vojvodina in same time, and usually the first was recorded as Saraz I and the second as Saraz II. Unfortunatelly many football-specialized internet websites merged the two and erroneously named the player described in this article as Geza Abraham Sarasz.
