{{refimprove|date=September 2018}}
The Reverend '''John Charles Carlile''', [[Order of the Companions of Honour|CH]], [[Order of the British Empire|CBE]] (c. 1861 – 16 August 1941) was a British Baptist minister.
Born in [[London]] of Scottish parents, he trained for the ministry at [[Spurgeon's College]]. He was minister of the Baptist Church on Abbey Street, [[Bermondsey]] from 1884 to 1893, in which year he was elected minister of Trinity Baptist Church, [[Marylebone]].<ref name=":0" /> In 1898 he took over a congregation in [[Folkestone]], [[Kent]], returning to London in the 1920s. In 1921 he was elected President of the [[Baptist Union]], and for many years was the editor of ''[[The Baptist Times]]''. From 1891 to 1897 he was a member of the [[London School Board]], representing [[Southwark (UK Parliament constituency)|Southwark]].
During World War I Carlile went to France five times to organize lectures for troops, and was one of the original members of the United Army and Navy Board. For his war services he was appointed a [[Order of the British Empire|CBE]] and decorated by the King of the Belgians.<ref name=":0">{{Cite news|url=|title=Rev. Dr. J. C. Carlile|last=|first=|date=18 August 1941|work=The Times|access-date=|page=6}}</ref> In 1929 he was appointed a [[Order of the Companions of Honour|Companion of Honour]].
